<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1926-10-14T01:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1926-10-14T01:00:00-05:00" n="662" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d662">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.512/412: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Mayer</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the
                                    <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1926-10-14T14:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">October 14,
                                        1926—2 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received October 14—5:50
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>478. My 469, October 12, 11 a.m.<note n="64" xml:id="d662fn64">Not
                                printed.</note> Following from American consul general, Canton:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“October 13, 3 p.m. Referring to my telegram of October 11,
                                        noon.<note n="64" xml:id="d662fn63">Not printed.</note> New
                                    taxes are now being collected on imports and exports. All China
                                        [<hi rend="italic">Chinese</hi>] and some foreigners are
                                    paying, but other foreigners are asking their consuls for
                                    instructions.</p>
                                <p>“Canton foreign Chambers [of] Commerce have written consular
                                    corps recommending that new taxes be collected through the
                                    Maritime Customs or on values fixed by Customs.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Mayer</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>